        <!-- ===== WHY 1Â°C MATTERS ===== -->
        <section class="content-section">
            <h2>
                <span data-lang="en">Why Does 1Â°C Matter?</span>
                <span data-lang="ja">ãªãœ1Â°CãŒå•é¡Œãªã®ã‹</span>
            </h2>
            
            <div class="story-box">
                <p class="story-lead" data-lang="en">
                    Reef-building corals survive within a narrow thermal range of 23â€“29Â°C. Just as a human body temperature rising from 36.5Â°C to 38.5Â°C signals serious illness, <span class="highlight">a 1Â°C anomaly in seawater can trigger coral bleaching</span>.
                </p>
                <p class="story-lead" data-lang="ja">
                    é€ ç¤ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã¯23ã€œ29Â°Cã¨ã„ã†ç‹­ã„æ¸©åº¦å¸¯ã§ç”Ÿå­˜ã—ã¦ã„ã¾ã™ã€‚äººé–“ã®ä½“æ¸©ãŒ36.5Â°Cã‹ã‚‰38.5Â°Cã«ä¸Šæ˜‡ã™ã‚Œã°æ·±åˆ»ãªç—…æ°—ã®å…†å€™ã§ã‚ã‚‹ã‚ˆã†ã«ã€<span class="highlight">æµ·æ°´ã®1Â°Cç•°å¸¸ãŒã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã®ç™½åŒ–ã‚’å¼•ãèµ·ã“ã™</span>å¯èƒ½æ€§ãŒã‚ã‚Šã¾ã™ã€‚
                </p>
                
                <p data-lang="en">
                    Sully et al. (2019) analyzed bleaching observations from <span class="emphasis">3,351 reef sites across 81 countries</span> and found that temperature is the primary driver of bleaching probability. Their global analysis demonstrated that even reefs with high biodiversity and good water quality cannot escape thermal stress when temperatures exceed local thresholds.
                </p>
                <p data-lang="ja">
                    Sully et al. (2019) ã¯<span class="emphasis">81ãƒ¶å›½3,351åœ°ç‚¹</span>ã®ç™½åŒ–è¦³å¯Ÿã‚’åˆ†æã—ã€æ¸©åº¦ãŒç™½åŒ–ç¢ºç‡ã®ä¸»è¦ãªæ±ºå®šå› å­ã§ã‚ã‚‹ã“ã¨ã‚’æ˜ã‚‰ã‹ã«ã—ã¾ã—ãŸã€‚é«˜ã„ç”Ÿç‰©å¤šæ§˜æ€§ã¨è‰¯å¥½ãªæ°´è³ªã‚’æŒã¤ãƒªãƒ¼ãƒ•ã§ã•ãˆã€æ¸©åº¦ãŒåœ°åŸŸã®é–¾å€¤ã‚’è¶…ãˆã‚‹ã¨ç†±ã‚¹ãƒˆãƒ¬ã‚¹ã‹ã‚‰é€ƒã‚Œã‚‰ã‚Œãªã„ã“ã¨ã‚’ç¤ºã—ã¾ã—ãŸã€‚
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- ===== HEAT STRESS ===== -->
        <section class="content-section">
            <h2>
                <span data-lang="en">Heat Stress: The Bleaching Threshold</span>
                <span data-lang="ja">é«˜æ¸©ã‚¹ãƒˆãƒ¬ã‚¹ï¼šç™½åŒ–é–¾å€¤</span>
            </h2>
            
            <div class="heat-section">
                <p class="section-intro">
                    <span data-lang="en">The operational definition of "thermal stress" for corals is based on a simple but powerful metric: MMM + 1Â°C.</span>
                    <span data-lang="ja">ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã®ã€Œç†±ã‚¹ãƒˆãƒ¬ã‚¹ã€ã®é‹ç”¨å®šç¾©ã¯ã€ã‚·ãƒ³ãƒ—ãƒ«ãªãŒã‚‰å¼·åŠ›ãªæŒ‡æ¨™ã«åŸºã¥ã„ã¦ã„ã¾ã™ï¼šMMM + 1Â°Cã€‚</span>
                </p>
                
                <div class="qa-block">
                    <div class="qa-question heat">
                        <span data-lang="en">What is MMM and why +1Â°C?</span>
                        <span data-lang="ja">MMMã¨ã¯ä½•ã‹ã€ãªãœ+1Â°Cãªã®ã‹ï¼Ÿ</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="qa-answer heat">
                        <span data-lang="en"><strong>MMM (Maximum Monthly Mean)</strong> is the highest monthly average SST from the climatology (typically 1985-2012). The +1Â°C threshold was established by NOAA Coral Reef Watch based on extensive field validation: when SST exceeds MMM by 1Â°C or more, bleaching probability rises sharply. This is not a biological constant but an <em>operational threshold</em> that has proven predictive across diverse reef systems.</span>
                        <span data-lang="ja"><strong>MMMï¼ˆMaximum Monthly Meanï¼‰</strong>ã¯æ°—å€™å­¦çš„ãªæœˆå¹³å‡SSTã®æœ€é«˜å€¤ï¼ˆé€šå¸¸1985-2012å¹´ï¼‰ã§ã™ã€‚+1Â°Cã®é–¾å€¤ã¯NOAA Coral Reef WatchãŒåºƒç¯„ãªãƒ•ã‚£ãƒ¼ãƒ«ãƒ‰æ¤œè¨¼ã«åŸºã¥ã„ã¦è¨­å®šã—ã¾ã—ãŸï¼šSSTãŒMMMã‚’1Â°Cä»¥ä¸Šè¶…ãˆã‚‹ã¨ã€ç™½åŒ–ç¢ºç‡ãŒæ€¥æ¿€ã«ä¸Šæ˜‡ã—ã¾ã™ã€‚ã“ã‚Œã¯ç”Ÿç‰©å­¦çš„å®šæ•°ã§ã¯ãªãã€å¤šæ§˜ãªãƒªãƒ¼ãƒ•ã‚·ã‚¹ãƒ†ãƒ ã§äºˆæ¸¬åŠ›ãŒå®Ÿè¨¼ã•ã‚ŒãŸ<em>é‹ç”¨é–¾å€¤</em>ã§ã™ã€‚</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="qa-block">
                    <div class="qa-question heat">
                        <span data-lang="en">Does a brief spike cause bleaching?</span>
                        <span data-lang="ja">ä¸€æ™‚çš„ãªã‚¹ãƒ‘ã‚¤ã‚¯ã¯ç™½åŒ–ã‚’å¼•ãèµ·ã“ã™ã‹ï¼Ÿ</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="qa-answer heat">
                        <span data-lang="en">Duration matters as much as intensity. A single day above threshold rarely causes mass bleaching; it's the <em>accumulation</em> of thermal stress that damages coral-zooxanthellae symbiosis. This is why NOAA developed <strong>DHW (Degree Heating Weeks)</strong>â€”a metric that integrates both intensity and duration. DHW â‰¥ 4 typically triggers significant bleaching; DHW â‰¥ 8 often causes mortality. <a href="dhw.html">â†’ See our DHW page</a></span>
                        <span data-lang="ja">æŒç¶šæ™‚é–“ã¯å¼·åº¦ã¨åŒæ§˜ã«é‡è¦ã§ã™ã€‚é–¾å€¤ã‚’è¶…ãˆã‚‹1æ—¥ã ã‘ã§å¤§è¦æ¨¡ç™½åŒ–ãŒèµ·ã“ã‚‹ã“ã¨ã¯ç¨€ã§ã™ã€‚ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´-è¤è™«è—»å…±ç”Ÿã‚’æå‚·ã™ã‚‹ã®ã¯ç†±ã‚¹ãƒˆãƒ¬ã‚¹ã®<em>è“„ç©</em>ã§ã™ã€‚NOAAãŒ<strong>DHWï¼ˆDegree Heating Weeksï¼‰</strong>ã‚’é–‹ç™ºã—ãŸç†ç”±ãŒã“ã‚Œã§ã™ã€‚DHW â‰¥ 4ã§é€šå¸¸æœ‰æ„ãªç™½åŒ–ãŒç™ºç”Ÿã€DHW â‰¥ 8ã§æ­»æ»…ãŒé »ç™ºã—ã¾ã™ã€‚<a href="dhw.html">â†’ DHWãƒšãƒ¼ã‚¸ã‚’è¦‹ã‚‹</a></span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="insight-box heat">
                    <strong class="heat"><span data-lang="en">Hughes et al. (2017) GBR Study:</span><span data-lang="ja">Hughes et al. (2017) GBRç ”ç©¶ï¼š</span></strong>
                    <span data-lang="en"> During the 2016 Great Barrier Reef bleaching event, 91% of reefs experienced some bleaching. The study showed that bleaching severity scaled predictably with cumulative heat exposure, with the northern GBR (highest DHW) suffering 67% coral mortality.</span>
                    <span data-lang="ja"> 2016å¹´ã‚°ãƒ¬ãƒ¼ãƒˆãƒãƒªã‚¢ãƒªãƒ¼ãƒ•ç™½åŒ–ã‚¤ãƒ™ãƒ³ãƒˆã§ã¯ã€91%ã®ãƒªãƒ¼ãƒ•ã§ä½•ã‚‰ã‹ã®ç™½åŒ–ãŒç™ºç”Ÿã€‚ã“ã®ç ”ç©¶ã¯ã€ç™½åŒ–ã®æ·±åˆ»åº¦ãŒç´¯ç©ç†±æ›éœ²ã¨äºˆæ¸¬å¯èƒ½ã«ã‚¹ã‚±ãƒ¼ãƒ«ã™ã‚‹ã“ã¨ã‚’ç¤ºã—ã€æœ€ã‚‚DHWãŒé«˜ã‹ã£ãŸåŒ—éƒ¨GBRã§ã¯67%ã®ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ãŒæ­»æ»…ã—ã¾ã—ãŸã€‚</span>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- ===== COLD STRESS ===== -->
        <section class="content-section">
            <h2>
                <span data-lang="en">Cold Stress: The Overlooked Threat</span>
                <span data-lang="ja">ä½æ¸©ã‚¹ãƒˆãƒ¬ã‚¹ï¼šè¦‹éã”ã•ã‚ŒãŸè„…å¨</span>
            </h2>
            
            <div class="cold-section">
                <p class="section-intro">
                    <span data-lang="en">While heat stress dominates headlines, cold stress can be equally devastatingâ€”particularly at subtropical reef margins like Ogasawara.</span>
                    <span data-lang="ja">ç†±ã‚¹ãƒˆãƒ¬ã‚¹ãŒãƒ‹ãƒ¥ãƒ¼ã‚¹ã‚’å¸­å·»ã™ã‚‹ä¸€æ–¹ã€ä½æ¸©ã‚¹ãƒˆãƒ¬ã‚¹ã‚‚åŒæ§˜ã«å£Šæ»…çš„ã¨ãªã‚Šãˆã¾ã™â€”â€”ç‰¹ã«å°ç¬ åŸã®ã‚ˆã†ãªäºœç†±å¸¯ãƒªãƒ¼ãƒ•ç¸è¾ºã§ã¯ã€‚</span>
                </p>
                
                <div class="qa-block">
                    <div class="qa-question cold">
                        <span data-lang="en">At what temperature does cold bleaching occur?</span>
                        <span data-lang="ja">ä½•åº¦ã§ä½æ¸©ç™½åŒ–ãŒèµ·ã“ã‚‹ã‹ï¼Ÿ</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="qa-answer cold">
                        <span data-lang="en">Saxby et al. (2003) documented cold bleaching in <em>Acropora</em> at 14Â°C, and Rich et al. (2022) reported bleaching in Red Sea corals below 16Â°C. The threshold varies by species and thermal history, but <strong>16â€“18Â°C</strong> is generally considered the danger zone for most Indo-Pacific corals.</span>
                        <span data-lang="ja">Saxby et al. (2003) ã¯14Â°Cã§<em>Acropora</em>ã®ä½æ¸©ç™½åŒ–ã‚’è¨˜éŒ²ã—ã€Rich et al. (2022) ã¯ç´…æµ·ã®ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã§16Â°Cä»¥ä¸‹ã§ã®ç™½åŒ–ã‚’å ±å‘Šã—ã¦ã„ã¾ã™ã€‚é–¾å€¤ã¯ç¨®ã¨æ¸©åº¦å±¥æ­´ã«ã‚ˆã£ã¦ç•°ãªã‚Šã¾ã™ãŒã€ã»ã¨ã‚“ã©ã®ã‚¤ãƒ³ãƒ‰å¤ªå¹³æ´‹ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã§ã¯<strong>16ã€œ18Â°C</strong>ãŒä¸€èˆ¬çš„ã«å±é™ºåŸŸã¨ã•ã‚Œã¦ã„ã¾ã™ã€‚</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="qa-block">
                    <div class="qa-question cold">
                        <span data-lang="en">Why is Ogasawara vulnerable?</span>
                        <span data-lang="ja">ãªãœå°ç¬ åŸã¯è„†å¼±ãªã®ã‹ï¼Ÿ</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="qa-answer cold">
                        <span data-lang="en">Ogasawara sits at latitude 27Â°Nâ€”the northern limit of reef formation in the Pacific. Winter SST regularly drops below 20Â°C for extended periods: <strong id="cold-ogasawara-inline">49</strong> days below 20Â°C in 2025 so far. While Okinawan reefs rarely experience prolonged cold, Ogasawara corals face chronic low-temperature stress that may limit recovery from summer heat events.</span>
                        <span data-lang="ja">å°ç¬ åŸã¯åŒ—ç·¯27Â°â€”å¤ªå¹³æ´‹ã®ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ç¤å½¢æˆåŒ—é™ã«ä½ç½®ã—ã¾ã™ã€‚å†¬å­£SSTã¯é•·æœŸé–“20Â°Cæœªæº€ã«ä¸‹ãŒã‚Šã¾ã™ï¼š<strong>2025å¹´ã¯ã“ã‚Œã¾ã§<span id="cold-ogasawara-inline-ja">49</span>æ—¥é–“20Â°Cæœªæº€</strong>ã€‚æ²–ç¸„ã®ãƒªãƒ¼ãƒ•ãŒé•·æœŸã®ä½æ¸©ã‚’çµŒé¨“ã™ã‚‹ã“ã¨ã¯ç¨€ã§ã™ãŒã€å°ç¬ åŸã®ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã¯å¤ã®é«˜æ¸©ã‚¤ãƒ™ãƒ³ãƒˆã‹ã‚‰ã®å›å¾©ã‚’åˆ¶é™ã™ã‚‹å¯èƒ½æ€§ã®ã‚ã‚‹æ…¢æ€§çš„ãªä½æ¸©ã‚¹ãƒˆãƒ¬ã‚¹ã«ç›´é¢ã—ã¦ã„ã¾ã™ã€‚</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="insight-box cold">
                    <strong class="cold"><span data-lang="en">El-Khaled et al. (2025) ED50 Metrics:</span><span data-lang="ja">El-Khaled et al. (2025) ED50æŒ‡æ¨™ï¼š</span></strong>
                    <span data-lang="en"> Recent research has developed standardized "ED50" metrics (temperature at which 50% photosynthetic efficiency is lost) for both heat and cold tolerance. This allows direct comparison of thermal sensitivity across species and populationsâ€”a breakthrough for predicting which corals can survive climate extremes.</span>
                    <span data-lang="ja"> æœ€è¿‘ã®ç ”ç©¶ã§ã¯ã€é«˜æ¸©ã¨ä½æ¸©ã®ä¸¡æ–¹ã®è€æ€§ã«ã¤ã„ã¦æ¨™æº–åŒ–ã•ã‚ŒãŸã€ŒED50ã€æŒ‡æ¨™ï¼ˆå…‰åˆæˆåŠ¹ç‡ãŒ50%å¤±ã‚ã‚Œã‚‹æ¸©åº¦ï¼‰ãŒé–‹ç™ºã•ã‚Œã¾ã—ãŸã€‚ã“ã‚Œã«ã‚ˆã‚Šã€ç¨®ã‚„é›†å›£é–“ã®ç†±æ„Ÿå—æ€§ã‚’ç›´æ¥æ¯”è¼ƒã§ãã‚‹ã‚ˆã†ã«ãªã‚Šã€æ°—å€™æ¥µç«¯ã‹ã‚‰ã©ã®ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ãŒç”Ÿãæ®‹ã‚Œã‚‹ã‹ã‚’äºˆæ¸¬ã™ã‚‹ä¸Šã§ã®ãƒ–ãƒ¬ãƒ¼ã‚¯ã‚¹ãƒ«ãƒ¼ã¨ãªã£ã¦ã„ã¾ã™ã€‚</span>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- ===== ADAPTATION ===== -->
        <section class="content-section">
            <h2>
                <span data-lang="en">Adaptation: Can Corals Adjust?</span>
                <span data-lang="ja">é©å¿œï¼šã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã¯é †å¿œã§ãã‚‹ã‹ï¼Ÿ</span>
            </h2>
            
            <div class="adapt-section">
                <p class="section-intro">
                    <span data-lang="en">The question of whether corals can adapt to warming oceans is one of the most urgent in reef science. Research reveals a complex picture spanning three timescales:</span>
                    <span data-lang="ja">ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ãŒæ¸©æš–åŒ–ã™ã‚‹æµ·ã«é©å¿œã§ãã‚‹ã‹ã¨ã„ã†å•ã„ã¯ã€ãƒªãƒ¼ãƒ•ç§‘å­¦ã§æœ€ã‚‚ç·Šæ€¥ãªèª²é¡Œã®ä¸€ã¤ã§ã™ã€‚ç ”ç©¶ã¯3ã¤ã®æ™‚é–“ã‚¹ã‚±ãƒ¼ãƒ«ã«ã¾ãŸãŒã‚‹è¤‡é›‘ãªæ§‹å›³ã‚’æ˜ã‚‰ã‹ã«ã—ã¦ã„ã¾ã™ï¼š</span>
                </p>
                
                <div class="wave-timeline">
                    <div class="wave-item">
                        <div class="wave-timing">
                            <span data-lang="en">Days to Weeks</span>
                            <span data-lang="ja">æ•°æ—¥ã€œæ•°é€±é–“</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="wave-title">
                            <span data-lang="en">Short-term Acclimatization</span>
                            <span data-lang="ja">çŸ­æœŸçš„é †åŒ–</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="wave-desc">
                            <span data-lang="en">Singh et al. (2023) showed that <em>Acropora</em> in Okinawa can improve heat tolerance after brief pre-exposure to elevated temperatures. This "thermal priming" doesn't change genetics but upregulates stress-response pathways.</span>
                            <span data-lang="ja">Singh et al. (2023) ã¯æ²–ç¸„ã®<em>Acropora</em>ãŒé«˜æ¸©ã¸ã®çŸ­æœŸå‰æ›éœ²å¾Œã«è€ç†±æ€§ã‚’å‘ä¸Šã•ã›ã‚‹ã“ã¨ã‚’ç¤ºã—ã¾ã—ãŸã€‚ã“ã®ã€Œç†±ãƒ—ãƒ©ã‚¤ãƒŸãƒ³ã‚°ã€ã¯éºä¼å­ã‚’å¤‰ãˆã¾ã›ã‚“ãŒã€ã‚¹ãƒˆãƒ¬ã‚¹å¿œç­”çµŒè·¯ã‚’ã‚¢ãƒƒãƒ—ãƒ¬ã‚®ãƒ¥ãƒ¬ãƒ¼ãƒˆã—ã¾ã™ã€‚</span>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="wave-item">
                        <div class="wave-timing">
                            <span data-lang="en">Months</span>
                            <span data-lang="ja">æ•°ãƒ¶æœˆ</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="wave-title">
                            <span data-lang="en">Seasonal Threshold Shifts</span>
                            <span data-lang="ja">å­£ç¯€çš„é–¾å€¤ã‚·ãƒ•ãƒˆ</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="wave-desc">
                            <span data-lang="en">GarcÃ­a et al. (2024) documented that bleaching thresholds shift seasonallyâ€”corals are more tolerant in late summer than early summer, suggesting physiological adjustment to ambient conditions.</span>
                            <span data-lang="ja">GarcÃ­a et al. (2024) ã¯ç™½åŒ–é–¾å€¤ãŒå­£ç¯€çš„ã«å¤‰å‹•ã™ã‚‹ã“ã¨ã‚’è¨˜éŒ²ã—ã¾ã—ãŸâ€”â€”ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã¯å¤åˆã‚ã‚ˆã‚Šå¤çµ‚ã‚ã‚Šã®æ–¹ãŒè€æ€§ãŒé«˜ãã€å‘¨å›²æ¡ä»¶ã¸ã®ç”Ÿç†çš„é †å¿œã‚’ç¤ºå”†ã—ã¦ã„ã¾ã™ã€‚</span>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="wave-item">
                        <div class="wave-timing">
                            <span data-lang="en">Generations</span>
                            <span data-lang="ja">ä¸–ä»£</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="wave-title">
                            <span data-lang="en">Genetic Adaptation</span>
                            <span data-lang="ja">éºä¼çš„é©å¿œ</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="wave-desc">
                            <span data-lang="en">Brown et al. (2024) found that habitat heterogeneityâ€”reefs with varied thermal microenvironmentsâ€”harbor greater genetic diversity for thermal tolerance. Drury et al. (2022) confirmed that thermal tolerance is heritable, offering hope for selective breeding in restoration programs.</span>
                            <span data-lang="ja">Brown et al. (2024) ã¯ç”Ÿæ¯åœ°ã®ä¸å‡ä¸€æ€§â€”â€”å¤šæ§˜ãªç†±å¾®ç’°å¢ƒã‚’æŒã¤ãƒªãƒ¼ãƒ•â€”â€”ãŒã‚ˆã‚Šå¤§ããªç†±è€æ€§ã®éºä¼çš„å¤šæ§˜æ€§ã‚’æŒã¤ã“ã¨ã‚’ç™ºè¦‹ã—ã¾ã—ãŸã€‚Drury et al. (2022) ã¯ç†±è€æ€§ãŒéºä¼æ€§ã§ã‚ã‚‹ã“ã¨ã‚’ç¢ºèªã—ã€å¾©å…ƒãƒ—ãƒ­ã‚°ãƒ©ãƒ ã§ã®é¸æŠçš„è‚²ç¨®ã«å¸Œæœ›ã‚’ä¸ãˆã¦ã„ã¾ã™ã€‚</span>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="insight-box adapt">
                    <strong class="adapt"><span data-lang="en">The Pace Problem:</span><span data-lang="ja">ãƒšãƒ¼ã‚¹ã®å•é¡Œï¼š</span></strong>
                    <span data-lang="en"> Coral generation times (5-10 years) cannot keep pace with the rate of ocean warming (~0.2Â°C per decade). Acclimatization may buy time, but without emissions reductions, even adapted corals will eventually face conditions beyond any biological threshold.</span>
                    <span data-lang="ja"> ã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã®ä¸–ä»£æ™‚é–“ï¼ˆ5ã€œ10å¹´ï¼‰ã¯æµ·æ´‹æ¸©æš–åŒ–ã®é€Ÿåº¦ï¼ˆç´„0.2Â°C/10å¹´ï¼‰ã«è¿½ã„ã¤ãã“ã¨ãŒã§ãã¾ã›ã‚“ã€‚é †åŒ–ã¯æ™‚é–“ã‚’ç¨¼ãã‹ã‚‚ã—ã‚Œã¾ã›ã‚“ãŒã€æ’å‡ºå‰Šæ¸›ãªã—ã«ã¯ã€é©å¿œã—ãŸã‚µãƒ³ã‚´ã§ã•ãˆæœ€çµ‚çš„ã«ã¯ã‚ã‚‰ã‚†ã‚‹ç”Ÿç‰©å­¦çš„é–¾å€¤ã‚’è¶…ãˆã‚‹æ¡ä»¶ã«ç›´é¢ã™ã‚‹ã“ã¨ã«ãªã‚Šã¾ã™ã€‚</span>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

